Peter Dada, Akure Many residents of Alade Idanre in the Idanre Local Government Area and Ayede Ogbese in the Akure North Local Government Area of Ondo State have been rendered homeless as flood submerged several houses and shops in both communities The flood occurred as a result of heavy rainfall on Sunday and Monday in the two communities. In Alade Idanre, some areas affected by the flood were Oke Mapo, Opa and Yaba Alade Idanre, among others, while in Ayede Ogbese, many areas were affected. It was gathered that property worth millions of naira were destroyed by the flood. Residents of both communities have called on the federal and state governments and other intervention agencies, especially the National Emergency Management Agency, to come to their aid. One of the victims, Mr Festus Olamiti, pleaded with the government to come to his aid, lamenting that his house, built over seven decades ago, had been destroyed by the flood. He stated that due to his old age, he had nobody to turn to and no income to fall back on. Another victim, Taye Akinyemi, a retiree, lamented that he had put all his savings to set up a fishery and everything inside the ponds had been washed away by the flood. Another victim, who identified herself simply as Bolatito, said amid sobs that she was left with nothing except the clothes on her at the time of the incident. She too appealed to the government and well-meaning Nigerians to help her. A resident of Ayede Ogbese, Mr Michael Adesina, said the flood happened because the river in the town overflowed its bank. He urged the state government to dredge the river to prevent a re-occurrence of the incident. Copyright PUNCH.
